    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Implements intended to spoon, scoop, and sometimes also to store, cosmetics. Best known as works from ancient Egypt, Greece, Rome, and elsewhere. These spoons were made from various materials such as wood, alabaster or ivory, and were often elaborately sculpted or decorated with symbolic imagery.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000093795/Encyclopedia Britannica Online (2002-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000093903/Brresc-Bautier, Louvre: The Collections (1991)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Oudegyptische lepelvormige houders die gebruikt werden om make-up in te bewaren en bereiden. Deze houders werden gemaakt uit verscheidene materialen, zoals hout, albast of ivoor, en vaak gebeeldhouwd naar of versierd met symbolische beeldtaal.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000087494/KMKG thesaurus</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000092241/KIK-IRPA thesaurus</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>用來盛取、舀出、有時甚至貯放化妝品的工具；最著名的製品來自古埃及、希臘、羅馬、與其他地方。這些勺子是用各種材料製成的，例如木頭，雪花石膏或象牙，並經常用象徵性的圖像精心雕刻或裝飾。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
